   Date: 9 Jan 89 00:48:24 GMT
   From: hedrick@rutgers.edu  (Charles Hedrick)

   &gt;nice if the root servers didn't have to deal with these bogus ".BITNET"
   &gt;and ".SPAN" domains.  

   The other possibility would be to MX .bitnet and .span -- and maybe
   even .uucp -- to appropriate gateways.  There are a lot of sites that
   define these domains locally.  

and with good reason: there are many, many instances where i (for i =
"any system maintainer at a particular place") know there are better
routes to .{span,bitnet,uucp,foonet} than the commonly-used gateways
(here at MIT we have a campus gateway to UUCP, and a BITNET gateway
&lt;MITVMA, one of the four "official" BITNET gateways&gt;).  

why should the root nameserver system know about the foibles and
features of each site (and why should it care about "domains" which
aren't?)

# Henry Mensch  /  &lt;henry@garp.mit.edu&gt;  /  E40-379 MIT,  Cambridge, MA
# {decvax,harvard,mit-eddie}!garp!henry   /  &lt;henry@uk.ac.sussex.cvaxa&gt;

